<paragraph id="6CA19A04ABDD4B6BFE26058C0082FB10" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E5488DC7BB05B273B7A846A18D02DD2A" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName id="572A589237C65CE3EC7861688BCFCA98" authorityName="Torres-Garcia, Gene and Dania Garcia" authorityYear="2022" class="Eurotiomycetes" family="Aspergillaceae" genus="Penicillium" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Penicillium sicoris" order="Eurotiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="sicoris">
<emphasis id="85182627B0A6A2CC6C8050E64EC188BB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Penicillium sicoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="20955EAC3AC955DB455476C0F2F0A9DC" genus="P." lsidName="P. mexicanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="mexicanum">
<emphasis id="ED670BF48EE6BC40D5433CC5EC164AC4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. mexicanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in series 
<taxonomicName id="D0FC0AB1593A503905D41EFED62C4AFF" genus="P." lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="series" series="Atramentosa">
<emphasis id="11B12860EED0AB99D433C136893940C2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">Atramentosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="25C5CE3DF69DAC3D69F94676C6758DC9" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Phylogenetic tree of Penicillium section Paradoxa based on ML analysis obtained by RAxML inferred from the combined tub 2, cmdA, ITS, and rpb 2 loci. Branch lengths are proportional to phylogenetic distance. Bootstrap support values / Bayesian posterior probability scores above 70 % / 0.95 are indicated on the nodes. Bold branches indicate bs / pp values 100 / 1. The tree is rooted to Penicillium species belonging to Penicillium section Turbata (P. madriti CBS 347.61, P. caprifimosum CBS 142990, P. bovifimosum CBS 102825 and P. turbatum CBS 383.48). The name in red is the new species described in this study. T = Ex-type strain." figureDoi="10.3897/mycokeys.86.73861.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/640602" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">3</figureCitation>
). Phenotypically, species of this series share a moderately fast colony growth and brown reverse on CYA and YES, and good growth on CREA without acid production (
<bibRefCitation id="AA68C0B07B0A5F5CA1FC7C3BDA5A9494" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.05.002" author="Houbraken, J" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="5 - 169" refId="B39" refString="Houbraken, J, Kocsube, S, Visagie, CM, Yilmaz, N, Wang, XC, Meijer, M, Kraak, B, Hubka, V, Bensch, K, Samson, RA, Frisvad, JC, 2020. Classification of Aspergillus, Penicillium, Talaromyces and related genera (Eurotiales): an overview of families, genera, subgenera, sections, series and species. Studies in Mycology 95: 5 - 169, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.05.002" title="Classification of Aspergillus, Penicillium, Talaromyces and related genera (Eurotiales): an overview of families, genera, subgenera, sections, series and species." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2020.05.002" volume="95" year="2020">Houbraken et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). However, our species differs in having an orange to grayish yellow reverse on CYA. In addition, 
<taxonomicName id="7745CF4A2ED9A4EBE65AB89A4275025C" genus="P." lsidName="P. sicoris" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="sicoris">
<emphasis id="8C4AE34A5DC9C136375D176316D50379" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. sicoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also differs from its counterpart in several micromorphological features: i.e., its conidiophores are bi- or terverticillate, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="67B05DA675380D74084602F7B5ADC0E7" genus="P." lsidName="P. mexicanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="mexicanum">
<emphasis id="39F756EB3BD2B152E177F47AA50BB14B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. mexicanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are ter- or quaterverticillate, stipes are shorter (25-215 vs. 65-370 
<normalizedToken id="1AA1A7F2B56503033A597D2032207FFD" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
), phialides shorter (4-7.5 vs. 7-10 
<normalizedToken id="2C0F50769034CA3029A4FAD0D6BC05D3" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) and metulae longer (7-20 vs. 8.5-15.5 
<normalizedToken id="32BE6B9E1ACADF3AA42D16DD68752032" originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
) than those of 
<taxonomicName id="BC0D44A4B12771C6E766C8A9737072C0" genus="P." lsidName="P. mexicanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="mexicanum">
<emphasis id="07A4E6D2F7D020E7D48BC2AB3D4E9E25" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. mexicanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and its conidia are predominantly globose to subglobose, whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="3AF31376FF6289219849A2B96FA0A145" genus="P." lsidName="P. mexicanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="mexicanum">
<emphasis id="E4C856FAB0D379AAFDACFBD957123F92" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. mexicanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are broadly ellipsoidal to ellipsoidal (
<bibRefCitation id="7746631B4AEF8D39C35251FDC44C5422" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2014.07.002" author="Visagie, CM" journalOrPublisher="Studies in Mycology" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" pagination="63 - 139" refId="B89" refString="Visagie, CM, Hirooka, Y, Tanney, JB, Whitfield, E, Mwange, K, Meijer, M, Asmend, AS, Seifert, KA, Samson, RA, 2014c. Aspergillus, Penicillium and Talaromyces isolated from house dust samples collected around the world. Studies in Mycology 78: 63 - 139, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2014.07.002" title="Aspergillus, Penicillium and Talaromyces isolated from house dust samples collected around the world." url="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.simyco.2014.07.002" volume="78" year="2014 c">Visagie et al. 2014c</bibRefCitation>
). Moreover, 
<taxonomicName id="2712D26A86DF72BD377A76D61E977E92" genus="P." lsidName="P. mexicanum" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="mexicanum">
<emphasis id="787BF6105C6C635B507DC131AB345FA9" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. mexicanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a more restrictive growth on CREA than 
<taxonomicName id="5EB360AA73E524D1EC9F6DD574ED103F" genus="P." lsidName="P. sicoris" pageId="0" pageNumber="103" rank="species" species="sicoris">
<emphasis id="1624F460AC449BA58293A3F8C505A063" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="103">P. sicoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(5-8 vs. 21-27 mm diam. after 7 d).
</paragraph>
